Introduction

In the renowned sport of baseball, the pitcher is entrusted with the task of getting a batter ruled out. To this end, pitchers employ a wide range of pitches of various speeds, spin-rates, angles, and more general harnessings of physics, to ultimately get a ball past the batter.

Baseball fans are interested in knowing the type of pitches that pitchers pitch1! This is not necessarily easily done by sight; camera angles aren’t necessarily conducive to recognizing the curvature of the pitch (and if a pitch is meant to confuse a batter, it’ll probably confuse you too).

So, can we use machine learning in our stead? Let’s try it!

Methods

In this report, we first take a look at some summary statistics and visualizations about how our features trend for each type of pitch, to get a feel for what we should consider when fitting our model. We then use a Decision Tree classifier to fit our features, trying several impurity criteria, depth maxima, minimum samples for splitting, and imputation strategies to achieve as high as possible of a classification accuracy.

Our data will be all the pitches from one pitcher, Shohei Ohtani, in 2022. This still gives us a plentiful 2628 rows to utilize, which is sufficient for modeling.

It’s a lot of tables and especially plots! Let’s break them down.

I prefer talking over visualizations than tables, so we’ll just gloss over what stands out in the tables. From Table 3 (a), we can get an idea of what Ohtani’s preferred pitches are. 37.4% of his pitches are sweepers and another 27% of them are 4-seam fastballs. His least-used pitch is the slider, at 2.4%. We should be weary when talking about the less-common pitches, as we may just not have enough data on them as the other pitches.

From Table 3 (b), Ohtani’s sinkers and 4-seam fastballs have the highest average velocities, around 97 mph. Curveballs have the lowest average velocity of 77.7 mph, but also vary the most, with a standard deviation of 3.2 mph. From Table 3 (c), sliders and sweepers are neck-and-neck for the highest average spin rate, about 2497 rpm and 2492 rpm respectively. Split-fingers have the lowest average spin rate of 1972.7 rpm.

Moving on to the plots! Looking at velocity versus spin rate in Figure 1, it seems that Ohtani’s split-fingers are a well-seperated pitch type from the pack (even then, there’s some cutters in that cluster). There’s a lot of overlap between curveballs, sweepers, and most cutters, and there’s another overlapping cluster of mostly 4-seam fastballs and some sinkers. Using these features as a Decision Tree parameter might be good for classifying split-fingers, but there is otherwise a significant amount of impurity from this pair of features.

Figure 2 is promising. Plotting between the pitch’s vertical movemetn and horizontal movement (catcher’s perspective), the pitch types are generally much more well-separated. There’s still a fair bit of area where the pitches blend in, but these could be helpful features for our Decision Tree.

Finally, let’s look at the last feature, stand, through Figure 3. Most of the pitches tend to be employed slightly more often when the batter is positioned on the left of their plate, but overall, the relative frequencies are not far from 50 / 50. The only significant pitch type is the sinker, which definitely seems to be employed most frequently when the batter is positioned on the right.

Now that we understand how our data look like with respect to pitch_type, we can begin to fit our model.

Models

# process data for ML
y_train = pitches_train["pitch_name"]
X_train = pitches_train.drop("pitch_name", axis=1)

numeric_cols = X_train.select_dtypes("number").columns
categorical_cols = X_train.select_dtypes("object").columns

numeric_transformer = Pipeline(
    [
        ("Numeric Imputer", SimpleImputer()),
        ("Standard Scaler", StandardScaler())
    ]
)

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(
    [
        ("Categorical Imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
        ("One-Hot Encoder", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore"))
    ]
)

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    [
        ("Numeric Transformer", numeric_transformer, numeric_cols),
        ("Categorical Transformer", categorical_transformer, categorical_cols)
    ]
)

pipeline = Pipeline([
    ("Preprocessor", preprocessor),
    ("Classifier", DecisionTreeClassifier())
])

param_grid = {
    "Preprocessor__Numeric Transformer__Numeric Imputer__strategy": ["mean", "median"], # For fun
    "Classifier__criterion": ["gini", "entropy"],
    "Classifier__splitter": ["best"],
    "Classifier__random_state": [42], # Get that randomness out of here
    "Classifier__max_depth": [None, 5, 10, 15, 20, 25],
    "Classifier__min_samples_split": np.arange(2, 20, 2)
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid, cv=5, scoring="accuracy")
# train models

start = timer()
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
end = timer()

display(grid_search)
print("Ran in {} seconds".format(end - start))
Ran in 19.521265551000397 seconds

240 models. Given the number of elements in our param_grid, we have fitted 240 different Decision Tree classifiers.

Makes sense that it took 18 seconds.

Anyways, the only classifier we’re trying here is a decision tree. We try two different imputation strategies for our numeric data, "mean" and "median", mostly for fun and curiosity. We try two impurity measures, "gini" and "entropy". We only use the "best" splitter type, and set a random state of 42 so that running this notebook gets the same results. For maximum node depth, we allow an infinite number, and then try values 5 to 25, incrementing by 5. For minimum samples-split, we try values 2 to 20, incrementing by 2.

Results

# report model 
pd.Series(grid_search.best_params_)
df_metrics = pd.DataFrame(grid_search.cv_results_)[["param_Classifier__criterion", "param_Classifier__max_depth", "param_Classifier__min_samples_split", "param_Preprocessor__Numeric Transformer__Numeric Imputer__strategy", "mean_test_score"]]
df_metrics.columns = ["Criterion", "Max depth", "Min. Samples Split", "Numeric Imputer", "Accuracy"]

df_metrics.sort_values("Accuracy", ascending=False).head(15)

The GridSearchCV object declares the best parameters to use "entropy", None or unbounded node depth, splitting nodes at a minimum of 18 samples, and replacing NaN values through "median" imputation.

Displaying the top 15 hyperparameter sets by descending accuracy score, we’re inclined to disagree. It seems that even 10 depth nodes were sufficient to achieve an accuracy exactly equal to the “best” model within 4 decimal places. Generally, the accuracy barely changes going down. "Gini" does shift the accuracy slightly down, but still not by much. The best min_samples_split does seem to be within 14 to 16.

Discussion

Despite the apparent “best params,” we disagree with the model chosen by the grid-search.

We would not want an overly-flexible model that fits to the training set’s “noise” alongside its true pattern, which is why we argue that choosing a decision tree with limited node depth would be more ideal than leaving it unbounded. It’s hard to tell which node depth is ideal though; they all get roughly the same results.

Keeping the minimum sample-split size generally higher than the default of 2 also lets the model be less biased, and Table 4 shows that it also just leads to a greater accuracy.

So, can our model accurately classify a pitcher’s pitches? Sort of! To be clear, the model’s very good at classifying Shohei Ohtani’s pitches, in 2022.

  • This does not guarantee us that it will be a good model for classifying other pitchers’ pitches. Different pichers have different strengths – possibly literally, in terms of physical ability. Pitchers could generally throw faster or slower pitches on average, or pitches with more or less spin. They may also have different preferences – Ohtani rarely does sinkers or sliders, but this may be less the case for other pitchers. This is nothing to say of new pitchers, who may introduce a totally new mixup, or even new pitches!

  • It also doesn’t guarantee we’ll even accurately predict Ohtani’s future pitches. Ohtani may pitch sinkers more often in the future than 4-seam fastballs or sweepers. During the off-season, he may even come up with different ways to pitch his usuals at different speeds. Good pitchers probably don’t do use one same trick for too long. Unless the model gets to keep up-to-date with Ohtani’s most recent pitches, it’ll fall behind eventually.

One last thing: could our model be used to classify a pitch in real-time, like the machine learning models used on television at MLB?

start = timer()
grid_search.predict(X_train)
end = timer()

print("Predicting on {} rows took {} seconds".format(X_train.shape[0], end - start))
print("Predicting on 1 row would take ~{} seconds".format((end - start)/ X_train.shape[0]))
Predicting on 2628 rows took 0.0053014000004623085 seconds
Predicting on 1 row would take ~2.0172754948486715e-06 seconds

Yes! It takes a fraction of a second for the model to predict on just one row of inputs, which is what would happen, since there’s only one pitch happening at a time. The bottleneck would not be the prediction model, but how fast the tracking technology can measure the pitch metrics.

Conclusion

If a decision tree were chosen to predict MLB pitches, we would choose one that uses entropy to calculate impurity, splits nodes at a minimum of 16 to 18 samples, and is limited to a maximum depth of 25 or less. This procures an accuracy of about 96%; predicting 96 out of 100 pitches. If the average MLB game sees 300 pitches, then we can expect around 12 mispredictions. This is up to an actual baseball fan to decide whether that’s good or not!

That being said, for a significantly better model, consider updating or refitting the model every season with the newest data, and maybe even create one model for each pitcher, for best results.
